snippet.textDisplay:
I hate that I know exactly how Mark felt when he lost his dad. My mom passed in February. I was angry, depressed, and numb. I lost a best friend. I was there when she took her final breath and it didn't feel real. It was all so quiet, then it got deadly silent. They thankfully took her off of the heart monitor when they transferred her from the critical care unit to end of life care, but it still was haunting.

For anyone who's lost a parent or a sibling, even a child, or literally anyone important in your life, it affects us all differently but it still hurts. If they were terribly ill, they're not sick and hurting anymore. If they succumbed to mental health, their torment is over, even though it was far too soon. If they were stolen from you, I hope that they're in a better place and that justice has or eventually will come. As long as you loved them, not matter how they left you, they will live on forever. Do what you can to continue your own life; keep pushing on, especially when life seems to beat you down. And if you are having trouble coping with losing someone, please... Please talk to someone. Anyone. I have a fantastic support system with my dad, my sisters, my extended family, even my psychiatrist and family physician. I hope to be adding a good friend as a boyfriend soon.

There are so many people lost to horrible things, natural things, accidental things, and purposeful things. We should honor these loved ones and cherished friends by refusing to forget them. Learn and remember that it does it get easier to cope with loss as time moves forward. But if you're struggling now, open up to someone... Anyone. Others love and care for you, too. Don't give up. Grief is measured in years. Not hours, not days, nor weeks or months. Years.

I approach the one year anniversary of my moms death and I fear it, but I welcome it with open arms, too. I can visit her whenever I want. I have a thumbprint memory ring that has her on it. She's always with me without being here. And that's what's most important.

Sorry for the long post. I think too many people refuse to acknowledge those who've passed, at least in the general U.S. culture. It's always macabre or wrong somehow. It's not. It's how life is. Can't have a story without a beginning and an end. And no one's story can never end. But they can live on through others.

snippet.textDisplay:
Emotional pain leads to suicide, almost never physical pain. It's hurts so bad and they have no way of feeling better that they think the only way to get out of it is death. If you know someone who hurts emotionally every day and it's led to them drinking heavily, doing drugs or it has made them want to do physical harm to them to try and find relief, find a way to help. They're suffering greatly.

My dad died when I was 12. My dog at 13, aunt, great aunt, grandfather all died in my teens. I was alone and had bad medical problems that sent me into a deep depression for more than 10 years. I had to pull myself out of the hole that life put me in. Believe me when I say that if you've experienced something that ruined your life, ive felt the pain you've been through, but I managed to pull myself out.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's weird; For me girl stories rank higher than deaths. I've had crippling pain, I even laid crying in a ditch once when young when a girl turned her back on me (don't want to explain further).
I guess, judging from other stories, I've been extremely unlucky.
It has shaped me as a person more than anything else and I've lost so much of my life because of it.

I think part of the reason is that I wanted to believe several times that "this could finally be it, the thing that fix me" and I started letting my guard down and always got shred to pieces at the worst possible times. Never gently either.

I'm still not a complete husk, but it's extremely difficult for me to form any meaningful bond with the opposite sex beyond aquaintances. I'm sure I've had girls along the way like me, and maybe it could had become something given time, but I just don't want to deal with the churning, gutwrenching, breathtaking and heartstopping pain anymore.

I'm not sure why I write this. I'm completely apathetic towards the whole thing. I guess maybe I want to change the world just the tiniest bit?
Maybe someone will read this and realize that it might be worth having some empathy and gentleness with these things, maybe someone will think twice about being narcissistic, decieving or exploiting at some point, remember this, and do the right thing... maybe.

Maybe someone will read this and realize that it might be worth having some empathy and gentleness with these things, maybe someone will think twice about being narcissistic, decieving or exploiting at some point, remember this, and do the right thing... maybe.

snippet.textDisplay: Mark, my husband lost his dad a month ago. It feels like last week still. It was entirely unexpected. He was a very active man and my husband's best friend. He lived 5 minutes away and stopped by the house all the time--with a pizza, with his motorcycle to show off, just to chat about work, just to chill before he took his dog for a walk. The week before he died, he was crawling around MY dad's attic to fix his ceiling that had collapsed. My husband was in shock for two weeks. I made all the arrangements for his father's cremation myself and set my husband's doctor appointments. I paid for a CT scan because he started attributing his panic attacks to heart attacks, which is what killed his father (his first and only heart attack killed him within an hour), and I knew nothing short of a medical professional telling him he was physical fit would make him feel better. Since then the panic attacks have stopped but we still find ourselves in the denial phase, which I never even considered I could succumb to. What they don't tell you about denial is that you KNOW the truth, but it still feels like he's just on vacation somewhere. I don't know when that train of thought is supposed to end.

snippet.textDisplay:
In terms of emotional pain, if I had to rate it 1-10 (very lengthy, as a warning)...

At a 1-2, my grandmothers and pets dying. I had a weird relationship with my emotions during my childhood, at some points it would be non-existent, at others I'd be mimicking what the mood was at an extreme rate. With being a sibling of a severely disabled kid, we sometimes risk being emotionally stunted due to extra necessary focus being put on our disabled siblings (and that's perfectly fine, they need that shit and a little extra help to become adjusted) so that might have affected my ability to empathize alongside social isolation (only having my family and no friends or other kids my age to hang out with).
My first pet was a Siamese fighting fish, the kind that puffed up if you puffed your face up, and should never be put in a tank alongside another fighting fish otherwise they'd kill each other. It started a trend of me being happy to spend my time with him, but it would end up being mom's pet fish very quickly, and she was the most sad when he finally passed at a ripe age of 3 1/2 years. This trend continued with my four pet mice, even when one of them grew a tumor and successfully underwent surgery for it, as well as a class pet that died at our home, especially when I suspected the previous carer had given it heatstroke when he handed the poor mouse over (we all took turns to care for it during the weekend. I never forgave that other kid for harming the mouse, I know what you did Fraser). Unlike rats, they don't really get attached to people or do tricks, but I loved setting up their cages to run around in and did a lot of the work cleaning and caring for them. They still ended up as mom's precious girls.
With my grandmothers, one died when I was 9 years old, the other when I was either 16 or 17. I never really was able to be close to them, they were just... there. I did help scratch scratchie cards (the gambling kind) during my childhood with one of them, and the other lived next door. I don't really remember crying at either funeral, I was just the emotional support for my parents and kind of grey-rocked the second funeral to the point where I got physically ill instead. There's times even now where I don't understand how people could be sad about someone dying, been called out over it. It's just... something I'm not capable of feeling sad about, even if it seems insensitive

At a 3 (on a good day), my Venephobia (fear of veins). I can't stand seeing veins on my wrists, face, body, etc. nor can I stand seeing veiny arms (ironic considering I'm doing weightlifting). Bothers me WAY less with dead bodies, though

At a 5, cutting off contact with a friend when I realized he was a narcissist and trying to use me to get his ex to dump his new girlfriend, that he didn't see me as a friend and accused me of doing nothing to help him when I went out of my way multiple times to help him diffuse the situation with him and his ex. It sucked because he's got a narcissist dad that's emotionally/financially abusive and a thieving POS, but there wasn't anything I could do except end the relationship and advised everyone being harassed by him to do the exact same for their sake.

At a 7, trying to murder undyne in the genocide route. It seems trivial to the other things, but fights like that one are worse by how long they last rather than intensity alone. The most painful part was how empty I felt when she finally died after dying about 50+ times, that was a pain I understood pretty well and grey-rocked until reaching sans, where I just stopped playing altogether

at a 9, trying to find a job and venephobia (on a bad day). My anxiety chose the perfect time to go through the roof every time I started job hunting that I haven't touched a job hunting app ever since. With Venephobia, however, I end up suffering a panic attack that lands me on the floor, trying to get control over my breathing again. This has happened twice with a common pattern of being afraid of my veins and arteries failing me, or my mother dying from something she found in her veins (she's fine, it was some weird orange blob that never got explained, but boy did I hit the ground hard when I heard the news about her blood test). I try my best to keep it at a 3 and not a 9

At a 7, trying to murder undyne in the genocide route. It seems trivial to the other things, but fights like that one are worse by how long they last rather than intensity alone. The most painful part was how empty I felt when she finally died after dying about 50+ times, that was a pain I understood pretty well and grey-rocked until reaching sans, where I just stopped playing altogether

at a 9, trying to find a job and venephobia (on a bad day). My anxiety chose the perfect time to go through the roof every time I started job hunting that I haven't touched a job hunting app ever since. With Venephobia, however, I end up suffering a panic attack that lands me on the floor, trying to get control over my breathing again. This has happened twice with a common pattern of being afraid of my veins and arteries failing me, or my mother dying from something she found in her veins (she's fine, it was some weird orange blob that never got explained, but boy did I hit the ground hard when I heard the news about her blood test). I try my best to keep it at a 3 and not a 9
